<subsection xml:id="subsec-rotation-and-congruence" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Rotation and Congruence</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Rotation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Deduce congruence from rotation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that rotation is a rigid transformation that preserves distance and angle. Define congruent figures as having the same shape and size. State that a figure and its image under rotation are always congruent.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Rotate a triangle <m>90°</m> clockwise about the origin and verify congruence by comparing side lengths. Demonstrate that corresponding sides and angles are equal after rotation. Apply the distance formula to calculate side lengths of original and rotated figures.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Use congruence from rotation to solve geometric problems. Identify rotational symmetry in real-world objects. Explain why rotation-based designs maintain structural integrity.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/rotation/rotation-and-congruence.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/rotation/step-by-step-guide_rotation-and-congruence.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Rotating and Comparing</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Groups
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Setup</title>
                <p>
                    Triangle <m>A(1,2)</m>, <m>B(4,1)</m>, <m>C(3,4)</m> on a coordinate grid.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Steps</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Plot triangle <m>ABC</m> and rotate <m>-90°</m> (clockwise) about the origin: <m>A'(2,-1)</m>, <m>B'(1,-4)</m>, <m>C'(4,-3)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Calculate side lengths using the distance formula:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>AB = \sqrt{(4-1)^2 + (1-2)^2} = \sqrt{9+1} = \sqrt{10}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>A'B' = \sqrt{(1-2)^2 + (-4+1)^2} = \sqrt{1+9} = \sqrt{10}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>BC = \sqrt{(3-4)^2 + (4-1)^2} = \sqrt{1+9} = \sqrt{10}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>B'C' = \sqrt{(4-1)^2 + (-3+4)^2} = \sqrt{9+1} = \sqrt{10}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>AC = \sqrt{(3-1)^2 + (4-2)^2} = \sqrt{4+4} = \sqrt{8}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>A'C' = \sqrt{(4-2)^2 + (-3+1)^2} = \sqrt{4+4} = \sqrt{8}</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Compare: The original and rotated triangles have the same shape, size, and side lengths.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                What transformation maps <m>\triangle ABC</m> to <m>\triangle A'B'C'</m>?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Circulate among groups, asking probing questions: <q>Are the triangles the same?</q>, <q>How did you check?</q>, <q>Does rotation change size?</q>, <q>What about angles?</q> Expected answers: all corresponding sides are equal, therefore the triangles are congruent; rotation preserves shape and size.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_1uyz93jv">
      <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_ygjycplx">
        <term>Work in groups</term>
      </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_apf7qscl">
          Copy the trangle <m>ABC</m>  and the point <m>D</m> on a graph paper. Using a ruler and a protractor, rotate the triangle <m>-90^\circ</m> about point <m>D.</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_o0mzqqwd">
          Draw a dotted line to connect vertex <m>A</m> to point <m>D</m>
        </p>
        <image>
          <latex-image  label="tri_one">
            \begin{tikzpicture}

              % Draw the grid lines
              \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-7,-5) grid (5,5);
              
              \draw[thick,blue](-5,3)--(-5,0)--(-2,0)--cycle;
              \fill[blue,opacity=0.5](-5,3)--(-5,0)--(-2,0)--cycle;
              \node[above] at (-5,3) {A};
              \node[left] at (-5,0) {B};
              \node[right] at (-2,0) {C};

              % Draw the point at (-3,-3)
              \fill[red] (-3,-3) circle (2pt);

              \node[left] at (-3,-3) {D};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p xml:id="auto_5gmvsh4g">
          Place a protractor at the line <m>AD</m> with the centre of the protractor at <m>D</m>  and measure <m>90^\circ.</m> 
           Using a ruler draw <m>DA'</m> such that <m>AD\,=\,DA'.</m>
        </p>
        <image>
          <latex-image  label="tri_two">
            \begin{tikzpicture}

            % Draw the grid lines
              \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-7,-5) grid (5,5);

              \draw[thick,blue](-5,3)--(-5,0)--(-2,0)--cycle;
              \fill[blue,opacity=0.5](-5,3)--(-5,0)--(-2,0)--cycle;
              \node[above] at (-5,3) {A};
              \node[left] at (-5,0) {B};
              \node[right] at (-2,0) {C};

              % Draw the point at (-3,-3)
              \fill[red] (-3,-3) circle (2pt);

              \node[left] at (-3,-3) {D};

              \draw[style=dashed,red](-5,3)--(-3,-3)--(3,-1);
              \node[above] at (3,-1) {A'};

              \draw(-3.1,-2.6)--(-2.7,-2.5)--(-2.6,-2.9);
              \node at (-2.5,-2.5) {$90^\circ$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p xml:id="auto_a8t6ewl0">
          Repeat the step above for for vertices <m>B \text{ and} C.</m>
        </p>
        <image>
          <latex-image label="tri_three">
            \begin{tikzpicture}

            % Draw the grid lines
              \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-7,-5) grid (5,5);

              \draw[thick,blue](-5,3)--(-5,0)--(-2,0)--cycle;
              \fill[blue,opacity=0.5](-5,3)--(-5,0)--(-2,0)--cycle;
              \node[above] at (-5,3) {A};
              \node[left] at (-5,0) {B};
              \node[right] at (-2,0) {C};

              % Draw the point at (-3,-3)
              \fill[red] (-3,-3) circle (2pt);

              \node[left] at (-3,-3) {D};

              \draw[style=dashed,red](-5,3)--(-3,-3)--(3,-1);
              \node[above] at (3,-1) {A'};

              \draw[style=dashed,orange](-5,0)--(-3,-3)--(0,-1);
              \node[above] at (0,-1) {B'};

              \draw[style=dashed,purple](-2,0)--(-3,-3)--(0,-4);
              \node[below] at (0,-4) {C'};

              \draw[blue](3,-1)--(0,-1)--(0,-4)--cycle;
              \fill[blue,opacity=0.5](3,-1)--(0,-1)--(0,-4)--cycle;

              
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </activity>

    <figure xml:id="fig-rotation-positive-negative">
      <caption>Interactive Activity: Rotation of Positive and Negative Angles</caption>
      <interactive xml:id="interactive-rotation-congruence" platform="jsxgraph" width="100%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/rotation-and-congruence.js">
          <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-rotation-congruence" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1"/>
          <instructions xml:id="inst-rotation-positive-negative">
              <p>
                  Use this interactive board to explore rotations around point <m>D</m>:
              </p>
              <p>
                  
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Adjust the Angle:</strong> Drag the slider at the top left to change the rotation angle. Notice that positive angles rotate the triangle anticlockwise, while negative angles rotate it clockwise.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Move the Centre:</strong> Drag the red point <m>D</m> to see how changing the centre of rotation affects the final position of the image.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Observe Congruence:</strong> No matter the angle or centre of rotation, notice that the size and shape of the green triangle always exactly match the blue triangle.
                    </li>
                </ul>
              </p>
          </instructions>
      </interactive>
  </figure>
    <insight>   
      <p xml:id="auto_d7ovwcof">
        Congruence refers to a relationship between two figures or objects, whereby, they are identical in size and shape.
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_z27zi36v">
        Rotation is a type of transformation that repositions an object but preserves the shape and size of the object.
        Thus, rotation produces congruent figures.
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_yh5nhbih">
        <m>\Delta ABC </m> and <m>\Delta A'B'C' </m> are similar in size and shape. Therefore, they are said to be directly congruent.
      </p>
    </insight> 

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Key Concepts</title>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Rotation is a <alert>rigid (isometric) transformation</alert> <mdash/> it preserves distances and angles. Therefore, the image is always congruent to the object.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Direct congruence:</alert> Rotation preserves orientation (unlike reflection, which reverses it).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Proving congruence after rotation:</alert> Calculate all side lengths using the distance formula, verify that corresponding sides are equal, and use SSS/SAS criteria.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Rotation about <alert>any point</alert> preserves congruence (not just the origin).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Rotational Symmetry and 3D</title>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Regular tetrahedron:</alert> has rotational symmetry axes <mdash/> vertex-to-opposite-face and edge-to-opposite-edge.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Cube:</alert> 13 axes of rotational symmetry (3 face-to-face, 4 body diagonal, 6 edge-to-edge).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Misconception Alert</title>
                <p>
                    <q>Rotation does NOT change orientation like reflection does.</q>
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Problem 1</title>
                <p>
                    Square <m>P(0,0)</m>, <m>Q(3,0)</m>, <m>R(3,3)</m>, <m>S(0,3)</m>. Rotate <m>90°</m> anticlockwise about the origin.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Image: <m>P'(0,0)</m>, <m>Q'(0,3)</m>, <m>R'(-3,3)</m>, <m>S'(-3,0)</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Verification: <m>PQ = 3 = P'Q'</m>, <m>QR = 3 = Q'R'</m>, <m>RS = 3 = R'S'</m>, <m>SP = 3 = S'P'</m>. Diagonal <m>PR = 3\sqrt{2} = P'R'</m>. Congruent by SSS.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Problem 2</title>
                <p>
                    Point <m>A(4,1)</m> is rotated to <m>A'(-1,4)</m>. What is the angle of rotation?
                </p>
                <p>
                    Original angle with <m>x</m>-axis: <m>\tan^{-1}(1/4)</m>. Image angle: <m>\tan^{-1}(4/{-1}) = \tan^{-1}(-4) = 180° - 76° = 104°</m>. Difference <m>\approx 90°</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>OA = \sqrt{17}</m>, <m>OA' = \sqrt{17}</m>. Therefore, the rotation is <m>90°</m> anticlockwise.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Problem 3 (3D)</title>
                <p>
                    Regular tetrahedron <mdash/> axes of rotational symmetry:
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                4 axes through a vertex and the centre of the opposite face, each of order 3 (<m>120°</m>, <m>240°</m>).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                3 axes through midpoints of opposite edges, each of order 2 (<m>180°</m>).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total: 12 rotational symmetries (including identity). Each face maps to another, so all faces are congruent.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_25qirt36">
      <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_bo03z477">
          Triangle <m>ABC</m> is mapped onto <m>A'B'C'</m> after a rotation of <m>-45^\circ</m> and centre of rotation <m>D.</m>
        </p>

        <image>
          <latex-image label="congruence_rotation_example">
            \begin{tikzpicture}

            % Draw the grid lines
            \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-5,-5) grid (5,5);

            % Define vertices of the triangle object
            \coordinate (A) at (-2,1); 
            \coordinate (B) at (0,4);
            \coordinate (C) at (0,-1);
            \coordinate (D) at (1,-2);

            % Draw edges of the triangle object
            \draw[blue,thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;
            \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.5] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

            %Label the object vertices
            \node[left] at (A) {A};
            \node[above] at (B) {B};
            \node[below] at (C) {C};
            \node[below] at (D)  {D};

            % Define vertices of the triangle image
            \coordinate (A') at (1,2.2); 
            \coordinate (B') at (4.6,3);
            \coordinate (C') at (1,-.8);

            % Draw edges of the triangle image
            \draw[blue,thick] (A') -- (B') -- (C') -- cycle;
            \fill[blue!30,opacity=0.5] (A') -- (B') -- (C') -- cycle;

            %Label the image vertices
            \node[above] at (A') {A'};
            \node[above] at (B') {B'};
            \node[below right] at (C') {C'};

            %Transformation dotted lines
            \draw[style=dashed,thick,red] (A) -- (D) -- (A');
            \draw[style=dashed,thick,orange] (B) -- (D) -- (B');
            \draw[style=dashed,thick,purple] (C) -- (D) -- (C');

            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>  
        </image>
        <p xml:id="auto_y3z48qup">
          <ul xml:id="auto_05708fxr">
            <li xml:id="auto_r6nonpfy">
              <p xml:id="auto_spnpa9ol">
                <m>\Delta ABC \text{ and } \Delta A'B'C'</m> have the same shape and size.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_gdaq33df">
              <p xml:id="auto_2zr3pfw2">
                The length of the corresponding sides of <m>\Delta ABC \text{ and } \Delta A'B'C'</m> are the same.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_8z2zi0vi">
              <p xml:id="auto_m39mb9ef">
                Every corresponding internal angle for the triangles remain the same.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_0325njvv">
          Therefore, <m>\Delta ABC \text{ and } \Delta A'B'C'</m> are said to be <term>directly congruent.</term> 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    
    <exercise xml:id="ex-congruence-of-figures-using-transformations">
        <stack label="stk-congruence-of-figures-using-transformations" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-3-Rotation/2-3-4-Rotation-and-Congruence/Congruence-of-Figures-Using-Transformations.xml"/>
    </exercise>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment and Reflection</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Exit Questions</title>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Q1:</alert> Why does rotation produce congruent figures? <mdash/> It preserves distances and angles (rigid/isometric transformation).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Q2:</alert> <m>A(2,3)</m>, <m>B(5,3)</m>, <m>C(4,6)</m> rotated <m>180°</m> about the origin. Find the vertices and verify one pair of sides. <m>A'(-2,-3)</m>, <m>B'(-5,-3)</m>, <m>C'(-4,-6)</m>. <m>AB = 3</m>, <m>A'B' = 3</m> ✓.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Q3:</alert> Name 3 real-world objects with rotational symmetry. <mdash/> Clock, wheel, fan blade, etc.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

